/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=ujkbpqflduvhi8o2iaadcla7v3&q1=Jewel&q2=Rock%2FAlternative&interval=20|title=Results - RPM - Library and Archives Canada - Rock/Alternative|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref>\n*B<span id=\"endnote_B\"></span>'''[[#ref B|^]]''' \"Again and Again\" was released as a double A-side single with \"Goodbye Alice in Wonderland\" in some countries.\n{{refend}}\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n\n===Tributes===\n*\"You Make Loving Fun\" (''Legacy: A Tribute to [[Fleetwood Mac]]'s [[Rumours (album)|Rumours]]'')\n*\"Body On Body\" (''[[Forever Words|Johnny Cash: Forever Words]]'')\n\n===Soundtracks===\n*\"All By Myself\" (''[[Clueless (film)|Clueless]]'' OST - Unreleased-Not available on soundtrack CD)\n*\"Emily\"  (''[[The Crossing Guard]]'' OST)\n*\"Sunshine Superman\" (''[[I Shot Andy Warhol]]'' OST)\n*\"Under the Water\" (''[[The Craft (film)|The Craft]]'' OST)\n*\"[[Have a Little Faith in Me]]\" (''[[Phenomenon (film)|Phenomenon]]'' OST)\n*\"Foolish Games (radio mix version)\" (''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'' OST)\n*\"What's Simple Is True\" (''[[Ride with the Devil (film)|Ride with the Devil]]'' OST)\n*\"Angel Standing By\"  (\"[[Return to Me]]\" OST)\n*\"Sweet Home Alabama\" (''[[Sweet Home Alabama (film)|Sweet Home Alabama]]'' OST)\n*\"Quest for Love\" (''[[Arthur and the Invisibles]]'' OST)\n*\"[[Stay Here Forever]]\" (''[[Valentine's Day (2010 film)|Valentine's Day]]'' OST)\n*\"Alaska: The Last Frontier Theme Song (Acoustic)\" (''[[Alaska: The Last Frontier|Alaska: The Last Frontier - The Soundtrack]]'')\n\n=== EP promos ===\n* 1994: ''Save the Linoleum'' (promo)\n* 1994: ''Shiva Diva Doo-Wop'' (promo)\n* 1995: ''You Were Meant for Me'' aka ''Phyllis Barnabee Finally Gets a Bra'' (promo PRCD 6416-2)\n* 1999: ''Bits and Baubles'' (promo)\n\n==Music videos==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Video\n! Director\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1996\n| \"Who Will Save Your Soul\"\n| [[Geoff Moore (Photographer / Director)|Geoff Moore]]\n|-\n| \"You Were Meant for Me\"\n| [[Lawrence Carroll]]\n|-\n| \"You Were Meant for Me\" <small>(Juan Patino Mix)</small>\n| [[Sean Penn]]\n|-\n| 1997\n| \"Foolish Games\"\n| [[Matthew Rolston]]\n|-\n| 1998\n| \"Hands\"\n| Nick Brandt\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1999\n| \"Down So Long\"\n| Lawrence Carroll\n|-\n| \"What's Simple Is True\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Matthew Rolston\n|-\n| \"Jupiter (Swallow the Moon)\"\n|-\n| 2001\n| \"Standing Still\"\n| [[Darren Grant]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2002\n| \"Break Me\"\n| Mike Lipscombe\n|-\n| \"This Way\"\n| Marcos Efron\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2003\n| \"Intuition\"\n| [[Marc Klasfeld]]\n|-\n| \"Stand\"\n| Chris Applebaum/Brand New School\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2006\n| \"Goodbye Alice in Wonderland\"\n|\n|-\n| \"Again and Again\"\n| Matthew Rolston\n|-\n| \"Good Day\"\n| [[Alan Ferguson (director)|Alan Ferguson]]\n|-\n| \"Stephenville, TX\"\n| Jake Maymudes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2007\n| \"Quest for Love\"\n| Isaac Mizrahi\n|-\n| \"Go Tell It on the Mountain\" <small>(featuring [[Toby Keith]])</small>\n| [[Michael Salomon]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2008\n| \"Stronger Woman\"\n| [[Trey Fanjoy]]\n|-\n| \"I Do\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Peter Zavadil]]\n|-\n| \"Til It Feels Like Cheating\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2010\n| \"Stay Here Forever\" \n|- \n| \"Satisfied\"\n|-\n| \"No Good in Goodbye\"\n| Justin Nolan Key\n|-\n| \"Ten\"\n| Peter Zavadil\n|-\n| 2013\n| \"Two Hearts Breaking\"\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| \"My Father's Daughter\" <small>(featuring [[Dolly Parton]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/jewel/1253509/my-fathers-daughter-featuring-dolly-parton.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Jewel : My Father's Daughter (Featuring Dolly Parton)|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=October 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| Tom Campbell\n|-\n| 2016\n| \"Pretty Faced Fool\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/jewel/1359560/pretty-faced-fool.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Jewel : Pretty Faced Fool|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=March 31, 2016}}</ref>\n| Adam Jones\n|-\n| 2016\n| \"Body On Body\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7O1gHCFiH60|title=Jewel - Body On Body (Johnny Cash: Forever Words)|publisher=[[YouTube.com]]|accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Jewel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jewel Discography}}\n\n[[Category:Works by Jewel (singer)|Discography]]\n[[Category:Country music discographies]]\n[[Category:Pop music discographies]]\n[[Category:Discographies of American artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist discography\n|Artist       = [[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]]\n|Image        = Jewel Kilcher 05-18-2016 -6 (26905196050).jpg\n|Caption      = Jewel performing in 2016\n|Studio       = 12\n|Live         = \n|Compilation  = 4\n|Video        = 5\n|Tribute      = 1\n|Singles      = 33\n|Music videos = 28\n|Soundtrack   = 7\n}}\nThe [[discography]] of [[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]], an American singer-songwriter, consists of 12 studio albums, four compilation albums, 33 singles and five video albums. She debuted in 1995 after signing with [[Atlantic Records]].<ref name=\"allmusicbio\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p22611/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=allmusic ((( Jewel > Biography )))|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|last=Ankeny|first=Jason|accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nJewel's debut album, ''[[Pieces of You]]'' was issued in February 1995. Although it was initially not successful, the lead single, \"[[Who Will Save Your Soul]]\" eventually reached No. 11 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], pressing the album to later sell over twelve million copies. In addition, \"[[You Were Meant for Me (Jewel song)|You Were Meant for Me]]\" and \"[[Foolish Games]]\" each became Top 10 hits on the same ''Billboard'' chart. Her second album ''[[Spirit (Jewel album)|Spirit]]'' was released in November 1998, certifying 4&times; Multi-Platinum in the United States. Its first single entitled \"[[Hands (Jewel song)|Hands]]\" reached No. 6 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 that year. Her 2001 release ''[[This Way (Jewel album)|This Way]]'' followed similar suit, certifying Platinum in the United States and producing the Top 30 hit, \"[[Standing Still (Jewel song)|Standing Still]]\".\n\nHer fourth album ''[[0304]]'' was released in June 2003 and aimed towards a more [[Pop music|pop]] sound. It reached No. 2 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and certified Gold in the United States. The album's sound did not bring as major success as her previous releases, with its first single becoming the only major hit. In May 2006, her sixth album entitled ''[[Goodbye Alice in Wonderland]]'' was released, reaching No. 8 in the United States. Its sound was a departure from ''0304'', as it sound contained more elements that had originated in her debut album. Working with the country band, [[Big and Rich]], Jewel issued her first country album in June 2008 titled ''[[Perfectly Clear]].''<ref name=\"allmusicbio\"/> The release reached No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums]] chart and spawned the major country hit, \"[[Stronger Woman]]\". Jewel has sold over 18.5 million records in the [[United States]] according to the [[Recording Industry Association of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=tblTopArt&action= |title=RIAA - Gold & Platinum - November 2, 2010: Top Selling Artists |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |accessdate=November 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725020825/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=tblTopArt&action= |archivedate=July 25, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Studio albums==\n\n===1990s albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"8\"| Peak cha